# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nextjs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] A static site can be considered as SSR (and can be generated using SSR infrastructure), but there are nuanced differences.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] Content of a static site is generated at build time, not at request time.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] Static sites often do not need to be deployed on a server at all, and can be served from a CDN.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] The SSR/CSR distinction is more meaningful for sites with dynamic content, for example live-updating or user-specific content.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] In these cases, for every request, the server generates the HTML content on-the-fly because it is unrealistic to pregenerate every possible page.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] The HTML file contains near-complete page content, and any JavaScript asset is only to enable interactivity.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] Both SSR and CSR have their performance tradeoffs, and a mix of SSR and CSR can be used to combine the benefits of both techniques.
[src:nextjs/glossary-ssr] For example, the server can generate a page skeleton with empty placeholders, and the client can fetch additional data and update the page as needed.
[src:nextjs/next-js] React documentation mentions Next.js among "Recommended Toolchains" advising it to developers when "building a server-rendered website with Node.js".
[src:nextjs/next-js] Where traditional React apps can only render their content in the client-side browser, Next.js extends this functionality to include applications rendered on the server-side.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The copyright and trademarks for Next.js are owned by Vercel, which also maintains and leads its open-source development.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js is a React framework that enables several extra features, including server-side rendering and static rendering.
[src:nextjs/next-js] React is a JavaScript library that is traditionally used to build web applications rendered in the client's browser with JavaScript.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Developers recognize several problems with this strategy however, such as not catering to users who do not have access to JavaScript or have disabled it, potential security issues, significantly extended page loading times, and harm to the site's overall search engine optimization.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Frameworks such as Next.js sidestep these problems by allowing some or all of the website to be rendered on the server-side before being sent to the client.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js is one of the most popular frameworks for React.
[src:nextjs/next-js] It is one of several recommended "toolchains" available when starting a new app, all of which provide a layer of abstraction to aid in common tasks.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js requires Node.js and can be initialized using npm.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Google has contributed to the Next.js project, including 43 pull requests in 2019.
[src:nextjs/next-js] As of October 2024, the framework is used by many large websites, including Walmart, Apple, Nike, Netflix, TikTok, Uber, Lyft, Starbucks and Spotify.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In early 2020, Vercel raised $21 million in Series A funding to support improvements to the software.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The framework's original author, Guillermo Rauch, is currently the CEO of Vercel, and the project's lead maintainer is Tim Neutkens.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js was first released as an open-source project on GitHub on October 25, 2016.
[src:nextjs/next-js] It was originally developed based on six principles: out-of-the-box functionality requiring no setup, JavaScript everywhere, all functions are written in JavaScript, automatic code-splitting and server-rendering, configurable data-fetching, anticipating requests, and simplifying deployment.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js 2.0 was announced in March 2017 including several improvements that made it easier to work with small websites.
[src:nextjs/next-js] It also increased the build efficiency and improved the scalability of the hot-module replacement feature.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Version 7.0 was released in September 2018 with improved error handling and support for React's context API for improved dynamic route handling.
[src:nextjs/next-js] This was also the first version to upgrade to Webpack 4.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Version 8.0 was released in February 2019 and was the first version to offer serverless deployment of applications, in which the code is split up into lambda functions that are run on demand.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The version also reduced the time and resources required for static exports and improved prefetch performance.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Version 9.3, announced in March 2020, included various optimizations and global Sass and CSS module support.
[src:nextjs/next-js] On July 27, 2020 Next.js version 9.5 was announced, adding new capabilities including incremental static regeneration, rewrites, and redirect support.
[src:nextjs/next-js] On June 15, 2021 Next.js version 11 was released, introducing among others: Webpack 5 support, preview of real-time collaborative coding functionality "Next.js Live", and experimental function of automatic conversion from Create React App to Next.js compatible form "Create React App Migration".
[src:nextjs/next-js] On October 26, 2021, Next.js 12 was released, adding a Rust compiler, making the compilation faster, AVIF support, Edge Functions & Middleware, and Native ESM & URL Imports.
[src:nextjs/next-js] On October 26, 2022, Vercel released Next.js 13.
[src:nextjs/next-js] This major release brought about a new routing pattern in beta, with the addition of the App Router that includes support for layouts, React Server Components, streaming, and a new set of data fetching methods.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Furthermore, Vercel announced a new toolchain for front-end development called Turbo, including Turbopack as a successor to Webpack, Turborepo for incremental build systems.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In May 2023, Vercel released Next.js 13.4.
[src:nextjs/next-js] This brought with it the stable version of App Router, which allows developers to use it in production.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In October 2023, Vercel released Next.js 14, which comes with improved memory management with using edge runtime.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In October 2024, Vercel released Next.js 15.
[src:nextjs/next-js] It introduces the Rust-based bundler Turbopack (which is faster than Webpack), support for React 19, and asynchronous request APIs.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In October 2025, Vercel released Next.js 16.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Perhaps the most noticeable feature, in terms of open-source, is the Build Adapters API, which allows for easier integration with hosting providers who have custom requirements, despite Vercel supporting self-deployment since 2016 already.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js supports styling with CSS as well as precompiled Scss and Sass, CSS-in-JS, and styled JSX.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In addition, it is built with TypeScript support and smart bundling.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The open-source transpiler SWC is used to transform and compile code into JavaScript usable by a browser.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Webpack, another open-source tool, is used to bundle the modules afterward, however it is currently being replaced with TurboPack.
[src:nextjs/next-js] All of these tools are used with npm in a terminal.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The main feature of Next.js is its use of server-side rendering to reduce the burden on web browsers and provide enhanced security.
[src:nextjs/next-js] This can be done for any part of the application or the entire system, allowing for content-rich pages to be singled out for server-side rendering.
[src:nextjs/next-js] It can also be done only for first-time visitors, to reduce the burden on web browsers that have yet to download any of the site's assets.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The "hot reloading" feature detects changes as they are made and re-renders the appropriate pages so the server avoids the need to be restarted.
[src:nextjs/next-js] This allows changes made to the application code to be immediately reflected in the web browser, though some browsers will require the page to be refreshed.
[src:nextjs/next-js] The software uses page-based routing for developer convenience and includes support for dynamic routing.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Other features include hot-module replacement so that modules can be replaced live, automatic code splitting, which only includes code necessary to load the page, and page prefetching to reduce load time.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js also supports Incremental Static Regeneration and static site generation - a compiled version of the website is usually built during build time and saved as a .next folder.
[src:nextjs/next-js] When a user makes a request, the pre-built version which are static HTML pages are cached and sent to them.
[src:nextjs/next-js] This makes the load time very fast, but it's not suitable for every website, particularly for interactive sites that change often and utilize a lot of user input.
[src:nextjs/next-js] In November 2025, security researcher Lachlan Davidson reported a vulnerability to the React team that allowed unauthenticated remote code execution through a flaw in the React Server Component deserialization protocol.
[src:nextjs/next-js] A fix was published to npm on December 3rd and publicly disclosed as CVE-2025-55182 ("React2Shell"), which received a CVSS score of 10.0.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Next.js versions 15.x and 16.x were affected downstream by this CVE, tracked separately as CVE-2025-66478, as the default App Router configuration was susceptible.
[src:nextjs/next-js] Amazon threat intelligence teams observed exploitation attempts by multiple Chinese state-nexus threat groups within hours of public disclosure.
[src:nextjs/next-js] On December 5th, CISA added the vulnerability to its Known Exploited Vulnerabilities (KEV) catalog.
[src:nextjs/next-js] On December 6, 2025, Vercel released the npm package fix-react2shell-next for updating to versions with the security fix applied.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React can be used to develop single-page, mobile, or server-rendered applications with frameworks like Next.js and React Router.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Because React is only concerned with the user interface and rendering components to the DOM, React applications often rely on libraries for routing and other client-side functionality.
[src:nextjs/react-software] A key advantage of React is that it only re-renders those parts of the page that have changed, avoiding unnecessary re-rendering of unchanged DOM elements.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React is used by an estimated 6% of all websites.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React adheres to the declarative programming paradigm.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Developers design views for each state of an application, and React updates and renders components when data changes.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This is in contrast with imperative programming.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React code is made of entities called components.
[src:nextjs/react-software] These components are modular and can be reused.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React applications typically consist of many layers of components.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The components are rendered to a root element in the DOM using the React DOM library.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The two primary ways of declaring components in React are through function components and class components.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Since React v16.8, using function components is the recommended way.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Function components, announced at React Conf 2018, and available since React v16.8, are declared with a function that accepts a single "props" argument and returns JSX (JavaScript XML).
[src:nextjs/react-software] Function components can use internal state with the `useState` Hook.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On February 16, 2019, React 16.8 was released to the public, introducing React Hooks.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Hooks are functions that let developers "hook into" React state and lifecycle features from function components.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Notably, Hooks do not work inside classes — they let developers use more features of React without classes.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React provides several built-in hooks such as `useState`, `useContext`, `useReducer`, `useMemo` and `useEffect`.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Others are documented in the Hooks API Reference.
[src:nextjs/react-software] `useState` and `useEffect`, which are the most commonly used, are for controlling state and side effects, respectively.
[src:nextjs/react-software] "Only call hooks from React functions" — do not call hooks from plain JavaScript functions so that stateful logic stays with the component.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Although these rules cannot be enforced at runtime, code analysis tools such as linters can be configured to detect many mistakes during development.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The rules apply to both usage of Hooks and the implementation of custom Hooks, which may call other Hooks.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Though a similar concept to Server Side Rendering, RSCs do not send corresponding JavaScript to the client as no hydration occurs.
[src:nextjs/react-software] As a result, they have no access to hooks.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Class components are declared using ES6 classes.
[src:nextjs/react-software] They behave the same way that function components do, but instead of using Hooks to manage state and lifecycle events, they use the lifecycle methods on the `React.Component` base class.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React itself does not come with built-in support for routing.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React is primarily a library for building user interfaces, and it does not include a full-fledged routing solution out of the box.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Third-party libraries can be used to handle routing in React applications, such as React Router.
[src:nextjs/react-software] It allows the developer to define routes, manage navigation, and handle URL changes in a React-friendly way.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Another notable feature is the use of a virtual Document Object Model, or Virtual DOM.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React creates an in-memory data-structure, similar to the browser DOM.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Every time components are rendered, the result is compared with the virtual DOM.
[src:nextjs/react-software] It then updates the browser's displayed DOM efficiently with only the computed differences.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This process is called **reconciliation**.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This allows the programmer to write code as if the entire page is rendered on each change, while React only renders the components that actually change.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This selective rendering provides a major performance boost.
[src:nextjs/react-software] When `ReactDOM.render` is called again for the same component and target, React represents the new UI state in the Virtual DOM and determines which parts (if any) of the living DOM needs to change.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Lifecycle methods for class-based components use a form of hooking that allows the execution of code at set points during a component's lifetime.
[src:nextjs/react-software] JSX, or JavaScript XML, is an extension to the JavaScript language syntax.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Similar in appearance to HTML, JSX provides a way to structure component rendering using syntax familiar to many developers.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React components are typically written using JSX, although they do not have to be (components may also be written in pure JavaScript).
[src:nextjs/react-software] During compilation, JSX is converted to JavaScript code.
[src:nextjs/react-software] JSX is similar to another extension syntax created by Facebook for PHP called XHP.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The basic architecture of React applies beyond rendering HTML in the browser.
[src:nextjs/react-software] For example, Facebook has dynamic charts that render to `<canvas>` tags, and Netflix and PayPal use universal loading to render identical HTML on both the server and client.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React can also be used to develop native apps for Android and iOS using React Native.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Server-side rendering (SSR) refers to the process of rendering a client-side JavaScript application on the server, rather than in the browser.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This can improve the performance of the application, especially for users on slower connections or devices.
[src:nextjs/react-software] With SSR, the initial HTML that is sent to the client includes the fully rendered UI of the application.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This allows the client's browser to display the UI immediately, rather than having to wait for the JavaScript to download and execute before rendering the UI.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React supports SSR, which allows developers to render React components on the server and send the resulting HTML to the client.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This can be useful for improving the performance of the application, as well as for search engine optimization purposes.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React does not attempt to provide a complete application library.
[src:nextjs/react-software] It is designed specifically for building user interfaces and therefore does not include many of the tools some developers might consider necessary to build an application.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This allows the choice of whichever libraries the developer prefers to accomplish tasks such as performing network access or local data storage.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Common patterns of usage have emerged as the library matures.
[src:nextjs/react-software] To support React's concept of unidirectional data flow (which might be contrasted with AngularJS's bidirectional flow), the *Flux* architecture was developed as an alternative to the popular model–view–controller architecture.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Flux features *actions* which are sent through a central *dispatcher* to a *store*, and changes to the store are propagated back to the view.
[src:nextjs/react-software] When used with React, this propagation is accomplished through component properties.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Since its conception, Flux has been superseded by libraries such as Redux and MobX.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Flux can be considered a variant of the observer pattern.
[src:nextjs/react-software] A React component under the Flux architecture should not directly modify any props passed to it, but should be passed callback functions that create *actions* which are sent by the dispatcher to modify the store.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The action is an object whose responsibility is to describe what has taken place: for example, an action describing one user "following" another might contain a user id, a target user id, and the type `USER_FOLLOWED_ANOTHER_USER`.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The stores, which can be thought of as models, can alter themselves in response to actions received from the dispatcher.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This pattern is sometimes expressed as "properties flow down, actions flow up".
[src:nextjs/react-software] Many implementations of Flux have been created since its inception, perhaps the most well-known being Redux, which features a single store, often called a single source of truth.
[src:nextjs/react-software] In February 2019, `useReducer` was introduced as a React hook in the 16.8 release.
[src:nextjs/react-software] It provides an API that is consistent with Redux, enabling developers to create Redux-like stores that are local to component states.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React was created by Jordan Walke, a software engineer at Facebook, Inc.
[src:nextjs/react-software] (now Meta), who initially developed a prototype called "F-Bolt" before later renaming it to "FaxJS".
[src:nextjs/react-software] This early version is documented in Jordan Walke's GitHub repository.[1] Influences for the project included XHP, an HTML component library for PHP.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React was first deployed on Facebook's News Feed in 2011 and subsequently integrated into Instagram in 2012.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React Native, which enables native Android, iOS, and UWP development with React, was announced at Facebook's React Conf in February 2015 and open-sourced in March 2015.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On April 18, 2017, Facebook announced React Fiber, a new set of internal algorithms for rendering, as opposed to React's old rendering algorithm, Stack.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React Fiber was to become the foundation of any future improvements and feature development of the React library.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The actual syntax for programming with React does not change; only the way that the syntax is executed has changed.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React's old rendering system, Stack, was developed at a time when the focus of the system on dynamic change was not understood.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Stack was slow to draw complex animation, for example, trying to accomplish all of it in one chunk.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Fiber breaks down animation into segments that can be spread out over multiple frames.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Likewise, the structure of a page can be broken into segments that may be maintained and updated separately.
[src:nextjs/react-software] JavaScript functions and virtual DOM objects are called "fibers", and each can be operated and updated separately, allowing for smoother on-screen rendering.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0 was released to the public.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React 16.0 introduced error boundaries, a new component type that catches JavaScript errors anywhere in its child tree and renders a fallback UI instead of crashing the app.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On October 20, 2020, the React team released React v17.0, notable as the first major release without major changes to the React developer-facing API.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On March 29, 2022, React 18 was released which introduced a new concurrent renderer, automatic batching and support for server side rendering with Suspense.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React 18 dropped support for Internet Explorer 11.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On December 5, 2024, React 19 was released.
[src:nextjs/react-software] This release introduced Actions, which simplify the process of making state updates using asynchronous functions rather than having to manually handle pending states, errors and optimistic updates.
[src:nextjs/react-software] React 19 also included support for server components and improved static site generation.
[src:nextjs/react-software] In October 2025, Meta announced that it would donate React, React Native, and JSX (JavaScript XML) to a new React Foundation, part of the Linux Foundation.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On 24 February 2026, The React Foundation officially launched with Meta Platforms, Inc. contributing the React project to the Foundation.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On 29 November 2025, a vulnerability CVE-2025-55182, also known as React2Shell was reported that allowed remote code execution.
[src:nextjs/react-software] It was assigned a CVSS highest score of 10.0.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On December 11, 2025, the React team disclosed additional vulnerabilities in React Server Components: denial-of-service issues (CVE-2025-55184 and CVE-2025-67779, CVSS 7.5) and a source code exposure issue (CVE-2025-55183, CVSS 5.3).
[src:nextjs/react-software] The initial public release of React in May 2013 used the Apache License 2.0.
[src:nextjs/react-software] Many expressed concerns that Facebook could unfairly exploit the termination clause or that integrating React into a product might complicate a startup company's future acquisition.
[src:nextjs/react-software] In August 2017, Facebook dismissed the Apache Foundation's downstream concerns and refused to reconsider their license.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The following month, WordPress decided to switch its Gutenberg and Calypso projects away from React.
[src:nextjs/react-software] On September 26, 2017, React 16.0.0 was released with the MIT license.
[src:nextjs/react-software] The MIT license change has also been backported to the 15.x release line with React 15.6.2.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:nextjs/server-side-rendering] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] SSGs typically consist of a template written in HTML with a templating system, such as Liquid (Jekyll) or Go template (Hugo).
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] The same structure (typically a Git repository) includes content in a plain-text format such as Markdown or reStructuredText, or in a structural meta format such as JSON or XML.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] A single plain-text file may correspond to a single web page.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] Alternatively, a single structural metadata file may correspond to an entire website if a single-page application framework like AngularJS is used.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] The website variable settings are stored in a plaintext configuration file `_config.yml` (YAML), `_config.toml` (TOML) or `_config.json` (JSON).
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] Page files typically also start with a YAML, TOML, or JSON preamble to define variables such as title, permalink, or date.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] Files with names that begin with an underscore (`_`) such as `_index.md` (as opposed to `index.md`) are considered templates or archetypes and are thus not rendered as pages themselves.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] Several hundred SSGs have been documented to exist, with the vast majority being written in languages that are already prominent on the web, such as Python, Go, JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:nextjs/static-site-generator] Many *server-side template systems* have the option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
