[src:nextjs/web-performance] The Performance API is a group of standards used to measure the performance of web applications.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] The Performance API allows high precision measurements that are based on time in potential sub-millisecond resolution and a stable monotonic clock that is not subject to system clock skew or adjustments.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] The high resolution timers are needed for accurate benchmarking instead of the less precise and non-monotonic `Date` timestamps.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming.notRestoredReasons` property reports information on why the current document was blocked from using the bfcache on navigation.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] Developers can use this information to identify pages that need updates to make them bfcache-compatible, thereby improving site performance.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] Navigation Timing provides metrics associated with navigating from one page to another via the PerformanceNavigationTiming API.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] For example, you can determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document, or log the time it took until DOM construction has finished and interaction with the DOM is possible.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] The Performance API doesn't provide performance data analysis, or visualizations.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] However, the Performance API is integrated well with developer tools and its data is often sent to analytics end points and libraries to record performance metrics which help you to evaluate the data to find performance bottlenecks affecting your users.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] This page provides an overview about what sorts of Performance API data exists, how it is collected, and how it can be accessed.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] Resource Timing enables retrieving and analyzing detailed network timing data for the loading of an application's resources.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to load a specific resource (such as an image or a script) either implicitly as part of page load or explicitly from JavaScript, for example using the `fetch()` API.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] Server-Timing allows servers to communicate metrics about the request-response cycle to the user agent.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] You can collect this information and act on server-side metrics in the same way as all the other metrics processed with the Performance API.
[src:nextjs/web-performance] Create application specific timestamps using the user timing API's "mark" and "measure" entry types using high-precision timestamps that are part of the browser's performance timeline.
